---
import BlogPostLayout from '../../components/BlogPostLayout.astro';

const post = {
  title: 'Lessons From Supporting Shopify Merchants',
  description:
    'What I have learned from troubleshooting hundreds of Shopify support tickets — patterns, common mistakes, and how to communicate technical fixes clearly.',
  category: 'Shopify',
};
---

<BlogPostLayout {...post}>
  <p>
    Supporting Shopify merchants has taught me that the best fix is not just the one that solves the problem, but the one that the merchant understands. Over hundreds of tickets, a few patterns keep showing up. This article shares the lessons that have made the biggest difference in how I approach support work.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3 text-theme">Always reproduce before diagnosing</h2>
  <p class="text-muted">
    It is tempting to jump straight to a solution based on the description, but every store has a unique combination of theme, apps, and custom code. Reproducing the issue first prevents wasted effort and often reveals the real cause much earlier than code inspection alone.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3 text-theme">Isolate third-party variables</h2>
  <p class="text-muted">
    The most common root causes involve apps that were recently installed or updated, browser extensions, or theme customizations. Removing variables one at a time is the fastest way to isolate a conflict. A single app embed can change how the entire page behaves.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3 text-theme">Explain cause and fix separately</h2>
  <p class="text-muted">
    Merchants want to know what happened and what was done. Writing the cause and fix as two distinct sections makes the response easier to read. It also gives support teams a reference they can reuse when the same issue comes up again.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3 text-theme">Document everything</h2>
  <p class="text-muted">
    Internal documentation and merchant-facing notes both save time. A short summary of the investigation, the root cause, and the solution can prevent repeat tickets and helps onboard new team members faster.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3 text-theme">Test in context, not just locally</h2>
  <p class="text-muted">
    A fix that works on a preview theme might fail on the live store because of different apps, caching, or content. Always verify the fix on the actual store environment before closing a ticket.
  </p>

  <p>
    Good support is part technical skill and part communication. When merchants understand the fix, they trust the solution more and are less likely to run into the same problem again.
  </p>
</BlogPostLayout>
